    {
      "title": "Passive Voice (الفعل المبني للمجهول)",
      "titleArabic": "الفعل المبني للمجهول",
      "content": [
        "The passive voice in Arabic is formed by omitting the subject (fā'il), and the object becomes the new subject (nā'ib al-fā'il). The verb form changes with specific vowel patterns."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Māḍī passive: first radical has ḍammah, second has kasrah",
        "Muḍāri' passive: similar vowel pattern changes",
        "Object becomes nā'ib al-fā'il (deputy subject)",
        "Feminine nā'ib al-fā'il requires feminine verb form"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "قَتَلَ → قُتِلَ", "english": "killed → was killed" },
        { "arabic": "يَقْتُلُ → يُقْتَلُ", "english": "kills → is killed" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Form III Verbs (فَاعَلَ)",
      "titleArabic": "باب فَاعَلَ",
      "content": [
        "Form III verbs are formed by inserting an alif after the first radical. This pattern often indicates reciprocal actions or doing something with/to someone, as well as trying or attempting an action."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Pattern: فَاعَلَ (fā'ala) with alif after first letter",
        "Two maṣdar patterns: مُفَاعَلَة and فِعَال",
        "Often reciprocal: كَتَبَ (to write) → كَاتَبَ (to correspond with)",
        "Can indicate pretended action: مَرِضَ (to be sick) → مَارَضَ (to feign sickness)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "سَافَرَ", "english": "to travel" },
        { "arabic": "كَاتَبَ", "english": "to correspond with" },
        { "arabic": "قَاتَلَ", "english": "to fight (with someone)" }
      ]
    }
  ],
